.START 

Stocks bounced back with the bond market, though a late bout of speculative selling combined with some computer-guided sell programs to trim the session's early gains. 

The Dow Jones Industrial Average closed 4.75 higher at 2663.94.
At one point, the average was up more than 23 points. 

Bargain-hunting after Monday's sell-off and a recovery in the Treasury bond market helped underpin stocks.
Prices rose at the opening, after the bond market showed little reaction to news that August durable goods orders rose 3.8%, a sharper advance than expected.
The dollar's stability despite central bank intervention helped boost the market as well. 

Volume came to 158,350,000 shares on the New York Stock Exchange, well ahead of Monday's 121,130,000.
But aside from buying interest in single-country stock funds and issues of movie companies, trading remained sluggish. 

"It's a crazy market, with little institutional activity," said Thomas R. Walsh, head of equity trading at Nikko Securities International. "I certainly think it's looking for direction and has been for some weeks now." 

Albert Harmon, a New York Stock Exchange floor broker for MKI Securities, said, "There is no impetus here -- no real buying, no real selling, and programs have had an inordinate impact because there is not much volume." 

Stocks of movie companies continued to rise as analysts reassessed the studios' value in the wake of Sony's reported $3 billion takeover bid for Columbia Pictures Entertainment.
Paramount Communications climbed 1 1/2 to 56 1/4 on Big Board composite volume of 1.2 million shares, MCA advanced 2 to 65 5/8 and Orion Pictures gained 5/8 to 22 3/4. 

Merrill Lynch analyst Harold Vogel, who raised Merrill's short-term investment rating on Paramount to "buy" from "neutral," told Dow Jones Professional Investor Report that he values the company at $80 a share in a takeover.
Mr. Vogel also said MCA could be valued at $110 a share to an acquirer. 

Separately, Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co. repeated buy recommendations on all three issues.
Analyst Mara Balsbaugh places a value of $90 a share on MCA if it were to be sold in pieces, Professional Investor Report said.
On that basis, she said, Paramount is worth $100 a share and Orion is worth $30 a share. 

Columbia, the Big Board's most active issue for the second consecutive session, closed down 1/8 to 26 1/4 after surging 5 1/4 Monday.
About 4.2 million shares changed hands.
Smith Barney lowered its rating on the stock, citing doubts that another bidder will challenge Sony, which rose 2 1/8 to 61 5/8. 

Coca-Cola, the owner of a 49% stake in Columbia, rose 1 1/8 to 64 1/8. 

Spain Fund, one of several single-country funds to benefit recently on heavy buying from Japanese investors, soared 12 to 38 3/4 on 1.4 million shares.
Traders said the stock was the target of a short squeeze, or an effort to force holders of short positions to cover at a loss. 

Other Big Board-traded funds to advance sharply included Thai Fund, which went up 3 1/2 to 26 1/2 on 1.3 million shares; Germany Fund, up 3 to 15 on 1.1 million shares, and Scudder New Asia Fund, up 1 1/8 to 15.
First Iberia Fund added 1 to 14 3/8 on the American Stock Exchange. 

Salomon Brothers priced the $80 million Chile Fund yesterday at $15 a share.
The offering was approximately 5.4 million shares.
The fund's manager is BEA Associates.
The fund closed at 16 1/4 on 1.2 million shares. 

International Business Machines, which introduced three new computer models for small businesses and a number of enhancements to its personal-computer line, added 1 1/4 to 117 1/2. 

Other blue-chip issues besides IBM and Coca-Cola to withstand the market's late slide included Philip Morris, which went up 1 1/8 to 156 5/8; General Motors, up 1 1/8 to 48 1/4; and Aluminum Co. of America, up 3/4 to 74 5/8. 

National Semiconductor gained 3/8 to 8 3/8 on 1.3 million shares as vague takeover rumors resurfaced.
The latest round of speculation centered on the possibility of a bid from a Japanese suitor, traders told Professional Investor Report. 

Upjohn, another rumored candidate for acquisition, advanced 5/8 to 37 3/8 on 1.5 million shares.
Bristol-Myers, which already has agreed to merge with Squibb, was unchanged at 50 1/8 as 1.3 million shares changed hands. 

Boston Edison rallied 1 to 18 7/8 on talk that the company may be nearing an agreement on its request for an $85.8 million rate increase.
The utility said only that settlement talks are continuing in an effort to resolve issues that surround its bid to recover certain costs tied to the Pilgrim nuclear power plant. 

UAL, which owns United Airlines, rose 2 1/2 to 276 1/2.
British Airways officials expressed confidence that U.S. regulators will approve its plans to invest in the proposed leveraged buy-out of the company.
British Airways dropped 3/4 to 34 1/2; the company announced plans for a rights offering of convertible bonds that would raise about two-thirds of the $750 million it has agreed to provide for the buy-out. 

Harley-Davidson climbed 1 7/8 to 39 and traded as high as 40 5/8 on rumors that Ford Motor might be interested in a takeover of the motorcycle manufacturer.
Harley said it hasn't been approached and isn't for sale, while Ford declined to comment. 

Toys 'R' Us advanced 1 1/2 to 36.
The company said it would establish a presence in Japan through a joint-venture arrangement with the Japanese unit of McDonald's. 

Katy Industries added 5/8 to 22 5/8.
Richard L. Otte, an Illinois investor, said he holds a 5.1% stake in the company "solely for investment." 

Precious-metals stocks, seen as overpriced by some when compared with the current price of gold and the companies' production costs, fared worse than any other Dow Jones industry group.
Homestake Mining dropped 7/8 to 15 3/4, Hecla Mining slipped 3/8 to 14 1/4, Battle Mountain Gold fell 1/4 to 15 3/8 and ASA Ltd. eased 5/8 to 45 5/8. 

The American Stock Exchange Index gained 0.79 to 382.19.
Volume totaled 14,080,000 shares, compared with 11,790,000 Monday.
There were 304 issues advancing, 275 declining and 266 unchanged. 

B.A.T Industries rose 3/16 to 13 1/4 on 2.9 million shares after proposing a restructuring aimed at increasing its stock price and fending off a takeover bid from a group led by investor Sir James Goldsmith.
Sir James said the group would vote in favor of the plan. 

